just_use card_stack.go

# label: ELEGANT
# role: encodes domain knowledge

Owns stack-level types and operations. Four notable shapes:

- **Cached stackType.** CardStack carries a cached StackType set by
  NewCardStack; MarshalJSON drops it and UnmarshalJSON re-derives it so
  stale caches can never ride the wire. (Elm side derives on demand —
  `CardStack.stackType` is a function, not a stored field. Different
  strategy, same wire shape because the field never travels anyway.)
- **Location is integer-only.** UnmarshalJSON decodes `top` / `left`
  into `int` directly; any float value on the wire fails decode. The
  older tolerance for fractional-pixel positions (Cat's legacy drag UI)
  is gone — canonical wire form is exact, and silent truncation of
  floats would mask sender bugs. See
  `feedback_no_indices_no_floats_in_drag.md`.
- **Strict stack identity.** `CardStack.Equals` compares same `Loc` AND
  same cards in the same order (`cardsEqualInOrder`). `BoardCard.State`
  is ignored (turn-accounting, not identity). Sequence equality — not
  multiset — so `[AC, AD, AS]` and `[AD, AC, AS]` at the same loc are
  different stacks. Conformance locked in
  `games/lynrummy/conformance/scenarios/referee.dsl`
  (`identity_reorder_breaks_match`).
- **maybeMerge allows incomplete (2-card) results.** Mid-turn boards
  legitimately contain partial stacks en route to a run or set; only
  Bogus and Dup are rejected. Semantics (no Incomplete at rest) are
  checked at turn boundaries, not per merge.

CanExtract encodes the three legal peel shapes (end / set-middle / run-
middle with both halves ≥ 3). Mirrors TS's can_extract exactly.
